      },
      "date": "2019-06-19 05:48:45.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1\n\n(1 comment)\n\nFirstly, there needs to be a second patch in this series that actually removes the cfs_get_random_bytes() function, or it will be dead code. \n\nSecondly, the distinction between the two functions is not (or at least was not) meaningless.  The problem is that (re)booting 10,000 or 20,000 diskless nodes at exactly the same time may cause the initial RNG state of two or more nodes to be the same, and result in the client UUIDs and/or initial RPC XID to be the same. This used to be seen on Cray Catamount systems, though is less likely on nodes that have high-res clocks and interrupts (which Catamount did not have).  Hence mixing the NID(s) into the PRNG seed.\n\nThis can be done better today by adding the client NID(s) into the kernel PRNG entropy pool at startup, and then using the kernel interface. This was done in Neil's original patch series, the rest of which is missing here, and is needed before this patch can land:\n\n  https://lore.kernel.org/patchwork/cover/864255/",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "68f35ab65dfc4ee095c96ed44ef1287b2e937436",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2019-06-19 05:58:42.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\nAh, I see that https://review.whamcloud.com/34170 has landed the PRNG seed part a few months ago, but we still need the follow-on patch to remove cfs_get_random_bytes() itself. That patch can be marked -1 temporarily to allow the function to be deprecated for some time before it is removed (maybe a month or two is enough to catch any active patches).",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "7f050ac31793a948b5f2f1ee5443a49b73aa783c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2019-06-19 06:23:09.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\n> James is doing it as two separate patches because that is they way\n > I did it upstream.  The next patch (508d5e0f4d45) removes a lot\n > more than just cfs_get_random_bytes().\n > \n > It is frustrating that we are drip-feed the patches rather than\n > seeing a whole series together, but that is one of the drawbacks of\n > forcing everything through gerrit, it seems.\n\nNeil, it is definitely possible to push a patch series to Gerrit.  If we want to delay the landing if the later patches in the series, they can be marked -1 with a clear comment why, then marked +1 or rebased when they are ready to land. That allows the whole series to be visible, and reduces the risk that later patches are forgotten.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "310a49880cab09efd03d39541a8c03e5fb06ed9f",
